description.texts.en:
Hello Kiva Community!

Meet Everline who is a crop and animal farmer and, a mother eager to provide the very best for her family.

She states that with her small income, she hasn’t been able to provide sufficient lighting through the electricity in her home. Her family has been using kerosene lamps, despite the toxic fumes that put the family at risk of contracting respiratory diseases.

Everline is kindly appealing for a loan to buy a solar lantern to provide adequate lighting, enabling her children to read well while at home. With the lantern’s dual charging capability, her husband will also be able to efficiently charge his phone. Kindly consider lending to her.
name: Everline
use: to buy a solar lantern to provide adequate lighting, enabling her children to read well while at home.

description.texts.en:
Abby is a caring mom from the Eldoret area, which is a luxuriant maize- and dairy-producing region in the Rift Valley Province of Kenya. She's very passionate, hardworking and eager to learn and take on new challenges.

These qualities have propelled her to be one of the most respected farmers in her village. She sells milk, poultry, maize and vegetables produced on her farm. She also has a personal business to make ends meet.

Abby is a go-getter and has a great desire to succeed in life. Of all her activities, dairy farming is closest to her heart. She enjoys waking up every morning to milk her cows and feed them with fodder that has a high nutrient value. She's so keen and close to her cows that she's named them, which makes Abby very proud. She feels fulfilled.

Abby is seeking an education loan to pay tuition fees for her youngest children, who are still in school.

She believes the knowledge and skills her children will get from school will help them to have a brighter future. Through education, her children will secure good jobs and be able to build good, modern houses.

Lend $25 or more toward this loan and empower her children’s lives.
name: Abby
use: to pay tuition fees for her youngest children, who are still in school.

description.texts.en:
Hello Kiva Community!

Meet Hellen, who is a crop and animal farmer, and a mother eager to provide the very best for her family.

She states that with her small income, she hasn’t been able to provide sufficient lighting through the electricity in her home. Her family has been using kerosene lamps, despite the toxic fumes that put the family at risk of contracting respiratory diseases.

Hellen is kindly appealing for a loan to buy a solar lantern to provide adequate lighting, enabling her children to read well while at home. With the lantern’s dual charging capability, her husband will also be able to efficiently charge his phone.

Kindly consider lending to her.
name: Hellen
use: to buy a solar lantern.

description.texts.en:
Jane is honest and hardworking. She adores her family and will do anything to keep them from going to bed hungry. She is from the Eldoret area of Kenya. She did not have the opportunity to advance her education to get a white-collar job.

Jane plans to succeed in life and has farmed for 12 years. She is experienced and has many farming techniques at her fingertips. She practices animal and crop farming to take care of her family's needs and provide a good education. She believes that education is the key to success for her children.

Jane requested a loan, which she will use to pay the school fees for her children. With the loan, her children will learn comfortably, and they will never be sent away because of a lack of tuition fees. Jane wants her children to have a bright future, and with this loan, she will be able to achieve this.
name: Jane
use: to pay the school fees for her children.

description.texts.en:
Veronique says: "I have been running a pharmacy for 12 years now. I received my starting capital from my husband, who also happens to be trained as a nurse.

The revenues from this business have really helped us to improve our living conditions, and to pay for our children's education and food. Thanks to this loan, I will stock up various pharmaceutical products with the goal of meeting customer demand and improving my revenues."
description.texts.fr:
J'exploite une pharmacie voilà maintenant 12 ans", nous confie Véronique. "Le fond de démarrage, je l'ai reçu de mon mari qui est aussi infirmier de formation.
Les revenus émanant de cette activité nous a beaucoup aidé dans l'amélioration de notre habitat, les études des enfants et la nourriture.
Avec ce crédit, je vais m'approvisionner en divers produits pharmaceutiques nécessaires afin d'essayer de satisfaire ma clientèle et d'améliorer mes revenus."
name: Famille Byamoto Group
use: to buy pharmaceutical products for resale.

description.texts.en:
Peter is a married man and together with his wife they are able to support their family. Peter does dairy farming for a living and he runs a retail shop, too, an activity which he has done for 12 years.

He is in need of this loan to purchase a stove. With an energy efficient stove, he will be able to save on other expenses, thereby increasing his income.

He has created employment for others through his dairy farming activities. He dreams of growing his retail business.
name: Peter Boro
use: to buy an energy efficient stove in order to save on expenses.

description.texts.en:
Michael is a 34-year-old single man. He supports his mother through his dairy farming business, which he was blessed to be able to start four years ago. He has serviced previous loans with Kenya ECLOF before without a problem.

His main challenge is not having enough milk to sell to his clients. He therefore intends to purchase a dairy cow with the loan, in order to increase the supply of milk that he sells to clients. Profits from his growing business will enable him service the loan comfortably.

He dreams of being a large milk distributor one day.
name: Michael Kimani
use: to buy a dairy cow in order to increase the supply of milk that he sells to clients.

description.texts.en:
Ellen’s source of income for the past three years has been from the operation of a grocery shop. She makes it easier for her neighbors to get grocery items such as canned fish, milk, sugar, rice, toothpaste, cooking oil, etc. to purchase. She is able to win the hearts of her customers with her smiles, which she gives to each of them irrespective of their ages.

Ellen is seeking financial assistance to help stock her shop. As a hardworking woman, she gives every assurance of repaying back the loan joyfully, once she knows she is going to benefit from it.

Ellen is married with two children, and lives with her family in Koforidua, in the Eastern Region of Ghana.
name: Ellen
use: to buy stocks of canned fish, milk, rice, sugar, and other grocery items to sell for increased revenue.

description.texts.en:
Meet 35-year-old Saffiatu from Moriba town branch. She is married with three children between the ages of 8 and 14 years old. Three of them are currently attending school.

Saffiatu runs a local produce and fuel sales business and sells firewood, charcoal, cassava, etc. She has been in this business for the past 15 years now and works nine hours per day and six days a week. Her family's other source of income comes from her husband.

Saffiatu says her main challenge is the slows sales sometimes.

Saffiatu requested this loan from BRAC to purchase more firewood and charcoal, as well as local produce, to increase her business. She says that the extra income from this loan will be used to educate her children.

In the future, she wants to see her business grow to a larger scale. She says thanks to BRAC and the Kiva community for their support.
name: Saffiatu
use: to purchase more firewood and charcoal, as well as local produce, to increase her business.

description.texts.en:
Tabitha is a married woman who is blessed with five children. She does poultry farming in her community. She enjoys this business because of its huge profits.

She intends to use the loan to buy more chicks for sale. Her main challenge is not having enough money to add capital to her growing business.

She has assisted the community around her by employing some youth who assist her in her business. She dreams of growing her business and educating her children.
name: Tabitha Mukethi
use: to add stock of more chicks for sale.

description.texts.en:
Anna is a thirty three year old mother of two children who are both at school. She is married and her husband is a self-employed builder. Anna sells plastic ware in Bindura town. She restocks mostly from Harare, but she was facing a cash inadequacy challenge that always hindered her business growth.

Due to cash shortages and harsh economic challenges, Anna decided to form a group so that she can borrow money from Thrive. She joined forces with three other friends who also conduct their businesses in Bindura town. They named their group Nhedzi. They formed their group specifically to access a loan for their business revival since every group member had the same cash problems.

Nhedzi group got a total amount of $1400. Anna’s portion of $400 was used to restock plastic ware even across the border so that she will be supplying it for wholesale and continue also in retail of plastic ware. She believes wholesaling of plastic is going to increase her sales.
name: Nhedzi Group
use: to restock plastic ware.

description.texts.en:
Twenty-six-year-old Rita is married with one child. She lives in Koforidua, the Regional Capital of the Eastern Region of Ghana.

The main source of income for Rita is from the sale of cosmetics. She sells different types of quality cosmetics to individuals in her community. For the past three years, her customers have enjoyed good customer services from her, a trait that her customers always commend her for.

Rita currently needs financial assistance to increase her stock of cosmetics, especially the new brands in the market. She hopes to attract new customers and maintain the old ones once she is able to get the latest of cosmetics in her shop.

In the future, she hopes to increase her working capital by saving her profits.
name: Rita
use: to buy varied stocks of cosmetics to sell for increased revenue.

description.texts.en:
Irene is a 23-year-old married woman with three children, two of whom are in school. She sells charcoal on the outskirts of Jinja. This has been her main source of income for the past four years. Irene also owns two dairy cows that provide milk that she can sell to various households for extra income.

She was recently contacted by a friend who is selling a Friesian cow so that she can pay her children’s school fees. Irene welcomed this opportunity because it would increase her milk production, but she is not financially able to buy the cow.

For this reason, Irene applied for a loan of 300,000 UGX to add to her savings so that she can buy the cow. She is optimistic that her milk production will increase and lead to more income, thus allowing her to provide for her family.

Irene appreciates the financial support so that she can expand her farm and transform her family’s standard of living.
name: Irene
use: to buy a Friesian cow.

description.texts.en:
Dorothy lives in Maara, Kenya with her family. On her farm she has four cows, three chickens and two horses that produce more than 100kg of manure every day. When she heard about a biodigester that was fed with manure and that produced biogas, she could not believe it, Dorothy realized that she can take advantage of the waste from her farm and offer her family many benefits and a better life quality. One of the benefits is that they can cook their food with the biogas produced by the biodigester Sistema Biobolsa, they will stop spending on the purchase of firewood and they will be able to take showers with hot water every day. With the savings they'll get from using the biodigester Sistema Biobolsa, Dorothy will be able to invest in her farm and improve the environment.

Dorothy's family will also increase their harvest because they will take advantage of the organic fertilizer produced by the biodigestor and will give the soil the necessary nutrients to produce high quality vegetables without chemical fertilizers.

This loan represents 42% of the total price of the biodigester; the remaining part is paid directly by Dorothy.
name: Dorothy
use: to purchase  a biodigester to expand her farm with renewable energy.

description.texts.en:
Nosimilo hardly spends a day at home. She sells from her car in different locations. Meanwhile she is working on finding a flea market table which she is hoping to find in central Harare. She is a married mother of two dependents. She is 35 years old and is staying in the Highfield suburb with her husband who is a truck driver.

Nosimilo is a cross border trader who travels to Zambia and South Africa to purchase electrical gadgets to order and other small items. She believes everyone is a potential customer and hence she markets to anyone she meets. This method of selling has proved to be quite good and profitable for her. She is realising that people are demanding a greater range of products than she is currently supplying. Nosimilo also noticed that new competitors are coming up and hence she needs to up her game.

Nosimilo came to Thrive with her friend to get another loan to further boost her business. The two have come a long way and they are in the Anengoni group. The two received a total loan of $1100. Nosimilo used $600 to restock more products such as winter wear, blankets and African attire materials.
name: Anengoni Group
use: to restock more products such as winter wear, blankets and African attire materials.

description.texts.en:
Maud, a 64-year-old lady, runs a poultry business. She came to Thrive six months ago and she was lent $250, and she was able to improve her poultry business. Maud sells her chickens in Goromonzi and Harare. Maud is able to supply many canteens in her area. She also sells secondhand clothes in her village as way to maximize her sales.

Maud is a widow and she has been doing well to provide food for her family. She is a mother of four children, and all her children have completed school. She only has grandchildren going to school.

Maud is applying for another loan since she has been having more customers who want her chickens. She was unable to meet their demand because of insufficient capital. Maud got a loan of $350 to buy a batch of 100 birds to supply her customers.
name: Descended Group
use: to buy a batch of 100 birds to supply her customers.

description.texts.en:
Arita's loan from Thrive Microfinance will be a big boost to her as she will be able to restock bales of formal trousers, shirts and also blankets as winter approaches.

Arita gained her entrepreneurial spirit at a young age from her mother. She started off rearing chickens at her mother’s house, then also started selling second hand clothes. When she started the second hand clothes she was selling locally, then found a market at the Shamva gold mines where she was selling to the gold panners who spend their money freely. She also sells fleece blankets and kitchen ware at times.

What makes Arita’s second hand clothing business different and more special is that she selects good grade clothing, washes them and irons them, leaving them looking brand new. This makes them more attractive to her clients, who are always looking forward to new clothing items from her. She now has a market table in Shamva where she has an employee who sells the items for her.

Arita resides in Waterfalls, Harare with her husband and infant son. Her son is her biggest inspiration and motivator as she wants him to get the best education she can possibly give him. At 34 years old, she still has a wish of achieving the dream of being able to help her child write homework. She has plans to start learning to read and write so that she can see the world in a better light through literature.
name: Arita
use: to restock bales of formal trousers, shirts and also blankets as winter approaches.

description.texts.en:
Enna is a 34-year-old hard working woman who lives in Southlands Park near Chitungwiza. She runs a good shop business at her house where she sells items like bathing soap, washing powder, flour, sugar cooking oil and bread. She is married and has 4 children whom she works hard to provide the best for.

She restocks her groceries weekly from wholesalers in town and Makoni and she makes good sales thanks to the proximity of her shop. She has been running her business for 4 years and another advantage is that she does not pay business rentals since the shop is located in her yard. Her day starts as early as 6 a.m., which is the time that she opens up her shop and closes up as late as 10 p.m daily.

Her customers have increased each day because of the good customer care and her knack for knowing just what her clients need and making sure that it is there. She teamed up with her two friends to form Mugadza business group in a bid to expand their businesses. They applied for a joint loan of $1,100 from Thrive Microfinance of which her portion of $300 will be used to restock more groceries and cosmetics for her shop.
name: Mugadza Group
use: to restock more groceries and cosmetics for her shop.

description.texts.en:
Godfred is in the middle in the picture. He used his previous loan to buy wood and finishing materials to upgrade his products. Godfred used the profit realized from the previous loan to finance his children's school fees and their upkeep.

Godfred and his group members have been with the field partner since 2012 and have a good credit history. The cost of doing business has gone up especially the finishing materials, due to the high standard set by the regulator. Godfred needs additional working capital support to buy wood and finishing materials for his work. Godfred will use the income from his business to support his family's upkeep. He will use his profits to payment of his children's school fees and reinvest the remaining profit into his business.

Godfred and his group members are grateful to their micro lenders for their kind support.
name: Nhyira Wood Carvers Group
use: to buy wood and finishing materials for crafting.

description.texts.en:
With only one leg, Chenai is making a difference among the disabled. She lost her left leg in a car accident some years ago and currently uses an artificial one. Chenai is a 42-year-old woman who resides in Harare. She is a tailor and specializes in sewing school uniforms. She supplies these uniforms to local schools and sometimes to rural areas. With the winter season about to start, she has been receiving more school wear winter orders.

This business has helped her in paying rentals and sending her children to school. Chenai is a widowed mother of three girls, all of whom are going to school; the first-born is studying at a local university.

Chenai passed through the Thrive training on financial literacy and received her first loan. Although they had some challenges with their first loan, they managed to repay all their dues.

Chenai got $300 to buy cloth and other materials needed for sewing uniforms. She wants to manufacture about 100 pairs of winter uniforms for boys and another set of 100 winter uniforms for girls.
name: Phase Extension Group
use: to buy cloth and other materials needed for sewing school uniforms.

description.texts.en:
This is Comfort, a 23-year-old hardworking woman who lives in Chorkor. She lives in a compound house with her husband and three children, who are all in school.

Comfort has taken out several loans from ID Ghana before. She is applying for a loan to buy more grocery items, such as milk, Milo, cooking oil and fruit drinks, to sell.

Comfort is a representative of the Faithfulness Group, which is composed of three members. Her greatest strengths as an entrepreneur are her determination and commitment.

Her dream for the future is to expand her business in order to buy and sell on a wholesale basis. She would like to thank all of her Kiva lenders for their generosity and support.
name: Faithfulness Group
use: to buy more grocery items, such as milk, Milo, cooking oil and fruit drinks, to sell.

description.texts.en:
Residing in Zengeza 2, in Chitungwiza, is a 34-year-old, married woman who is very hard-working and eager to expand her business. She has more than eight years of experience running a tuck shop, where she sells a variety of groceries and cosmetics. Her name is Milliana, and she is a proud mother of three children. Her tuck shop has become known for long operating hours. This has endeared her to the locals, and she is gaining more customers.

She is a determined woman who dedicates her time to her business, and she values every customer’s needs. Milliana performs a variety of roles that enable the day-to-day running of her tuck shop, which she rents. She is responsible for daily storekeeping and is relieved by her daughter once every week when she goes out to restock.

After hearing about the loans offered by Thrive Microfinance, Milliana formed a group, along with her three business associates, which they named Charmel Green. They then attended a financial literacy training course and applied for a joint business loan. The women got a combined loan of $1400, which they plan to use to expand their various business projects. Milliana used her loan of $350 to restock her tuck shop with more groceries.
name: Charmel Group
use: to restock her tuck shop with more groceries.

description.texts.en:
Memory is a married 35-year-old mother of three children all school-going. She is running a good tuck shop business in Nyatsime and has been doing so for more than three years. She is now very popular in her local area because of her ability to stock a wide variety of goods and also the fact that she also accepts mobile phone money transfers as a form of payment.

Memory restocks daily from the central business district in Harare and from Mbare wholesalers. She usually restocks with the previous day’s revenue using about $60 per day per day. Her average daily sales can get up to $80 per day, with bad days giving her around $45. Her tuck shop is at a strategic point and attracts a large chunk of the Nyatsime market share.

Memory and her friends formed a group named Nqobile meaning victory. All the women have thriving businesses which include poultry, cross border trading and grocery selling. As a group they received a total some of $1,200 from Thrive Microfinance to finance the working capital of their businesses. The group is receiving these funds for the first time and Memory wishes to use her $300 portion to invest more into her tuck shop. She also liked the business training she received and is planning to use that knowledge to grow her business.
name: Nqobile Group
use: to invest more into her tuck shop.

description.texts.en:
Bridget is a cross-border trader. She travels to neighboring South Africa to purchase groceries. She is a distinguished supplier of groceries in Harare. Most of the tuck shop operators in the area depend on her for their supply of groceries. She has been in this business for the past six years. She continues working hard because she realizes that this business contributes meaningfully to her family’s upkeep.

Bridget is married, and her husband is a pastor at a local church. She has three children, all of whom attend local schools in Harare, where she stays. Seeing the need to feed her children, dress them, and educate them, Bridget is energized to work extra hard in order to provide for her family. Bridget used her portion of $300 to improve her inventory levels since the demand for groceries continues to increase.
name: Renisha Group
use: to improve her inventory levels since the demand for groceries continues to increase.

description.texts.en:
Meet 45-year-old Augusta from the Moriba town branch. She is married with six children.

Augusta runs a retail shop and sells milk, sugar, cocoa, pens, books, soap, paste, batteries, cigarettes, insect repellant, etc. She has been in this business for the past ten years now and works twelve hours per day, six days a week. Her other source of income is from selling cloth. Augusta says her main challenge is packing in and out of the store every morning and evening.

Augusta requested this loan from Brac to purchase more provisions, toiletries, cosmetics, clothing, etc. to increase her business. She says that the extra income from this loan will improve and add to her business. In the future, she wants to grow her shop and improve her clothing business. She says thanks to Brac and the Kiva community for their support.
name: Augusta
use: to purchase more provisions, toiletries, cosmetics, clothing, etc.

description.texts.en:
Gladys is a 51-year-old single mother and has two children, ages 21 and 23 years. She sells clothes at Dansoman. Gladys has been engaged in this business for four years now.

With this new loan, Gladys will be able to get a permanent place (a store) to sell her clothes. She hopes to expand her business in the next five years. She will use the profit to support her children's education.

Thank you, Kiva lenders, for supporting Gladys' business!
name: Gladys
use: to get a permanent place to sell her clothes (a store).

description.texts.en:
Meet 39-year-old Janet from Moriba Town branch. She is married and has four children. Janet runs a retail business and sells sardines, milk, Ovaltine, sugar, cocoa, biscuits, sweets, rice, palm oil, local produce, etc. She has been in this business for the past 10 years now and works 10 hours per day and 6 days per week. Her other source of income comes from her husband. Janet says her main challenge is that sometimes sales are slow.

Janet has requested this loan from BRAC to purchase more palm oil, rice, charcoal, water, etc. to increase her business. She says that the extra income from this loan will help to take care of her children. In the future, she wants to expand into a big shop. She says thanks to BRAC and the Kiva community for their support.
name: Janet
use: to purchase more palm oil, rice, charcoal, water, etc.

description.texts.en:
Meet 32-year-old Ishmatu from Moriba town. She is married with three children between the ages of nine and 18 years old.

Ishmatu runs a retail business and sells biscuits, corn flakes, milk, cheese, cheese balls, etc. She has been in this business for the past ten years now and work ten hours a day, six days a week. Her other source of income is from her husband. Ishmatu says her main challenge is transportation of goods.

Ishmatu requested this loan from Brac to purchase more corn flakes, milk, cheese, cheese balls, etc. to increase her sales. She says that the extra income from this loan will improve her situation a lot and add to her business.

In the future she wants to pay fees for her children and increase her business. She says thanks to Brac and the Kiva community for their support.
name: Ishmatu
use: to purchase more corn flakes, milk, cheese, cheese balls etc.

description.texts.en:
Gakeni is a single mother of two children. She farms and sells khat and intends to acquire more inventory with this loan so that she can grow her business. Her challenge is having enough capital so that she can acquire more khat to meet the demand.

Gakeni has taken out previous loans before and successfully repaid them. She dreams of buying land in the future as an investment and providing for her children’s education.
name: Felanzia Gakeni
use: to acquire more inventory of khat to meet demand.

description.texts.en:
Art has always been an inborn talent for 34-year-old Charity, residing in Chitungwiza. She has been running her art business for many years at her home. This is where she spends most of her time, intricately painting different artifacts that she sells to different art galleries in Zimbabwe and also to individuals.

She believes in uniqueness and originality, and this has aided her to become a renowned artist. She has a backyard room that she uses as drawing and painting studio. The room is nicely decorated with different drawings taken from her personal imagination. Charity is a hardworking, married woman blessed with three school-going children, for whom she strives to provide the best.

She has also started a cross-border business of restocking groceries monthly from South Africa and supplying to different tuck shops in Chitungwiza. She carries with her artworks to sell in South Africa, so that she can hit two birds with one stone. In a bid to further expand her businesses, she returned to Thrive Microfinance, where she and her friend were previously given business loans.

The pair are the remaining members of Good Hope Group and have been loyal Thrive clients. They recently took a joint loan of $2,000, of which Charity’s portion was $1,000. She used her portion to restock paint and drawing equipment, as well as groceries for her cross-border business.
name: Good Hope Group
use: to restock more paint and drawing equipment, as well as groceries for her cross-border business.

description.texts.en:
Meet 45-year-old Rugiatu from Moriba town. She is married with five children between the ages of 12 and 25 years old.

Rugiatu runs a retail business and sells sardines, milk, ovaltine, sugar, cocoa, biscuits, sweets, rice, palm oil, mayonnaise, luncheon meat, baked beans, etc. She has been in this business for the past eight years now and works ten hours a day, six days a week. Her other source of income is from her husband. Rugiatu says her main challenge is slow sales sometimes.

Rugiatu requested this loan from Brac to purchase more food market provisions to increase her business. She says that the extra income from this loan will help to take care of her children. In the future, she wants to expand into a big shop. She says thanks to Brac and the Kiva community for their support.
name: Rugiatu
use: to purchase more food market provisions.

description.texts.en:
Monica is 51 and married. She has 4 adult children and she lives with her young grandchildren who are attending primary school. She lives in her own house.

With the amount of the loan, she plans to buy construction materials such as rebar, beams, rods, sand, and stone.

This is her second loan. With her previous loan, she bought construction material.

Her dream is to grow as a businesswoman.
description.texts.pt:
A senhora Monica têm  51 anos de idade, vive maritalmente, mae de 4  filhos maior de idade, e vive com seu netos menores de idade que frequentam ensino primario, e vive na casa própria. 
Com o valor do empréstimo pretende comprar material de construção tais como ferro, barrotes, varroes, areia e pedras.
Trata se do segundo empréstimo, com anterior comprou material de construção.
Têm como sonho crescer nos negocios.
name: Monica
use: to buy construction materials.

description.texts.en:
Rutendo is a 34-year-old woman who resides in Harare. She buys and sells clothes and groceries from her home. She has been in this business for the past five years and she has amassed enough knowledge and skills to survive in this difficult economy. Rutendo’s husband is employed at a local transport company as a truck driver.

She has been able to look after her children very well even when she has pressure from her business. This has been easy for her since she operates her grocery stall at her home. One of her two children is now going to school while the youngest one is likely to start primary school next year.

Rutendo is grateful for Thrive and its partners for the loan she received last year, since it helped her earn more profits from which she is assisting her husband in building their residential stand in Ruwa Harare. She used this loan to add to her stock of clothes and groceries.
name: Elgrand Group
use: to add stock of clothes and groceries.

description.texts.en:
Tafadzwa belongs to a vibrant group of three members called Candy. The group has just received a total sum of $1,250 to finance their various businesses.

Tafadzwa is a 35-year-old single mother of three children, with two currently at school. She is running a tuck shop business at her house in St. Mary’s, Chitungwiza. The business has been running for seven months now. She used to sell second-hand clothes. She has switched to the grocery business and has built a nice structure at her house, with shelves and all.

Tafadzwa restocks from Harare town and from wholesalers in her local area every Wednesday and Friday with at least $65. At the site visit, she had a business value of $250. Her shop is open daily, and she makes average daily sales of $20.

Tafadzwa is expecting her business to grow further as she wants to run the tuck shop business and second hand clothes business concurrently if she can get adequate capital. The $400 loan was used to restock her tuck shop.
name: Candy Group
use: to restock her tuck shop.

description.texts.en:
Florence started her preschool business more than 20 years ago using funds from her savings and assistance from her husband. In Norton, Auntie Flo’s preschool is one of the most famous preschools since some of the elders attended there. With her great experience, Florence has been able to withstand the competition.

Florence currently has about 90 children enrolled at her preschool, and she uses the help of three other teachers. She has also enrolled four orphaned children for free. Florence is a widow currently staying with her late sister’s son. She has identified that her preschool’s furniture is getting out-dated and she spent her portion of the loan on new furniture for her preschool.
name: Twinlakes Group
use: to buy new furniture for her preschool.

description.texts.en:
Lenah is a happily married woman who takes care of her grandchildren. She is a farmer, and it is a job she loves as it meets her needs well.

She intends to use this loan to boost her farming activities. She dreams of purchasing a lorry in the future to aid her in her business. She also dreams of seeing her grandchildren get a good education to secure them a bright future.
name: Lenah Mukwanjiru
use: to boost a farming business with fertilizers etc.

description.texts.en:
Milka is a 43-year-old woman who stays in Zvimba. She is involved in the business of raising and selling broiler chickens. For more than 4 years, this business has helped her contribute to the welfare of her family. She used to raise chickens in batches of 100 broilers at a time. But through the loan she received last year from Thrive Microfinance, she has managed to raise broiler chickens in batches of 150 birds at a time. However, this is way below her capacity since she has a fowl run which can house up to 400 chickens.

Milka has 2 children; her husband is employed as a general hand worker at a local manufacturing company. Milka and her family are currently staying in a 3-room cottage and it is Milka’s desire that she will be able to raise enough money to construct a bigger home since her family is growing.

Milka used her portion of the loan to start raising and selling broiler chickens in batches of 200 birds at a time. This will in turn allow her to enjoy a profit of at least $400 compared to the $300 profit she has been making. She hopes that this will help her continue saving for construction of her home.
name: Discovery Group
use: to start raising and selling broiler chickens in batches of 200 birds at a time.

description.texts.en:
Mines is 38 years old and married. He is a teacher and is the father of 3 young children who attend primary school. He lives in his own house.

With the amount of the loan, he plans to buy construction materials such as rebar, beams, rods, zinc sheets, sand, and stone.

This is his first loan. He plans to request another to continue work on his project.

He has a dream to put all of his children through school until they complete higher education.
description.texts.pt:
A senhora Mines têm 38 anos de idade, vive maritalmente, professor pai de 3 filhos menor de idade, que frequentam ensino primário, e vive na casa própria. 
Com o valor do empréstimo pretende comprar material de construção tais como ferro, barrotes, varroes, chapas de zinco, areia e pedras.
Ė primeiro empréstimo, ha plano de pedir outro valor para continuar com a sua obra.
Têm como sonho formar todos os seus filhos ate concluir nivel superior.
name: Mines
use: to buy construction materials.

description.texts.en:
Martha is a resident of Kasoa, which is located in the Central Region of Ghana. She is 44 years old.

Martha earns a living from the sale of smocks, a locally made cotton cloth garment. She has been in this business for the past two years. Martha started this business after she raised some money from selling drinks and pastries on a very small scale. She went into the business of selling smocks because she is interested in promoting locally made products. Martha believes it is her duty to promote her culture. She is able to attract all types of customers, both locals and tourists.

Martha is seeking financial assistance to help her buy more smocks to sell. As a hardworking woman, she assures the Kiva lenders that she will pay back the loan without any delays. She expresses her thanks in advance for the help.
name: Martha
use: to buy smocks to sell.

description.texts.en:
Merry is 27 years old. She is married and blessed with two school-going children. She is a beverage seller and owns a shop that sells soft drinks at both wholesale and retail prices. She has been in this business for three years. She normally opens her business at 6:00 a.m and closes at 9:00 p.m. She earns profit.

This will be Merry's third loan request from Tujijenge Tanzania. She used her previous loan to buy more drinks to sell. She earned profit that she used to open a beauty salon and repay the loan. She managed to pay back the loan successfully. She is applying for this loan to buy more stock of soft drinks such as mineral water, juice, soda, and energy drinks. Her dream is to be rich.

Merry will be responsible for paying back the loan.
name: Merry
use: to buy more stock of soft drinks such as mineral water, juice, soda, and energy drinks.

description.texts.en:
Jose is 47 years old. He is single and lives with a partner. He is the father of 3 children. 2 of them attend secondary school and 1 is an adult. He lives in his own house.

With the amount of the loan, he plans to buy construction materials such as metal sheets, beams, cement, sand, and wire.

This is his first loan. He plans to request another to continue construction on his house.

His dream is to help his children find employment.
description.texts.pt:
O senhor  Jose têm  47  anos de idade, solteiro, vive maritalmente, pai de 3  filhos dos quais ,  2 frequenta ensino  secundario e 1 maior de idade,  vive em  casa própria.
Com o valor do empréstimo pretende comprar material de construção tais como: Chapas, barrotes cimento, areia e arrame.
Ė primeiro empréstimo, e tem plano de pedir outro para continuar com a construção da sua casa. 
Têm como sonho ajudar os filhos a empregar-se .
name: Jose
use: to buy construction materials.

description.texts.en:
Catarina is 51 years old and married. She is the mother of 4 adult children who are completing higher education. She lives in her own house.

With the amount of the loan, she plans to buy construction materials such as cement, beams, rods, and metal sheets.

This is her second loan. With the first, she bought products for her grocery store.

Her dream is to finish her home.
description.texts.pt:
A  senhora  Catarina têm 51 anos de idade, vive maritalmente, mae de 4 filhos maiores de idade, que frequentam ensino superior, e vive na casa própria. 
Com o valor do empréstimo pretende comprar material de construção tais como cimentos, barrotes, varroes, chapas.
Trata se do segundo empréstimo, e com primeiro comprou produtos para sua mercearia.
Têm como sonho concluir sua casa.
name: Catarina
use: to buy construction materials.

description.texts.en: Rose is a mother of five children. She sells bananas to meet her family's needs and she now intends to add more stock of bananas using the loan to enable her to meet the demand. It is her first loan and she intends to pay back the loan from her profits. She dreams of educating her children to university level.
name: Rose
use: to add more stock of bananas.

description.texts.en:
Doris is a 61-year-old woman and has been selling kenkey (a traditional maize-based dish) for over a decade. A single mother with five children, Doris aspires to move from living in the same condition for over 30 years. Due to the lack of capital to increase her stock of maize, she has been unable to boost her output despite the high demand for the kenkey she sells.

Doris will use this loan to buy stock in a large quantity and probably travel to the villages to buy it herself. She is hopeful that this will help boost stock and increase her profit significantly.

Thank you, Kiva lenders, for supporting Doris' business!
name: Doris
use: to buy more maize to make kenkey (a traditional dish) to sell and increase her income.

description.texts.en:
Isaac is a 42-year-old man who lives in Chorkor, a very busy area located in Accra, the capital of Ghana. He has lived there for some years in a compound house in his community.

Isaac has taken out two loans with ID Ghana before. He is now applying for a loan to buy enough tools used to manufacture jewelry for sale.

He is a member of the Brazil Group, which is composed of four members. His greatest strengths as an entrepreneur are his determination and commitment.
name: Brazil Group
use: to buy enough tools for the manufacturing of jewelries to sell.

description.texts.en:
Recho is a returning Kiva borrower who has an impeccable credit history. She lives in a small mud house in the Siongiroi area of Kenya. Despite a difficult living situation and general lack of access to the outside world (internet connection), she is a hardworking farmer. She began farming ten years ago. Today she has achieved great milestones in terms of diversifying beyond vegetable farming by introducing farm animals, such as dairy cows and poultry.

Recho has managed to take care of her children with her income that comes from selling the milk from her cows. She has always wanted to take care of another dairy cow, but a lack of capital has prevented her from doing so. She is now seeking a loan to buy an additional dairy cow to improve her milk vending business. The cow she intends to buy is a breed that produces between 10-13 liters of milk a day. With this cow, she will produce more milk, which will translate into more income. Demand for milk in the Siongiroi area is high, but the supply is low. So, through this loan, Recho is going to have more milk and comfortably meet demand.

Recho's vision is to keep even more dairy cows so that she will be able to build a bio digester, which would help her to save more energy.

Be inspired this month and show a mom love by clicking the lend button!
name: Recho
use: to buy an additional dairy cow to improve her milk vending business so that in the future she can build a bio digester that will help her produce clean energy.

description.texts.en:
Purity always strives for success no matter how difficult it may seem. She is married to a teacher and they are blessed with four children, three of whom are still in school.

She commenced with a vegetable stall at her front yard in Unit A in 2014 which made her a visible and popular person in her neighborhood. This gave her an advantage that when the vegetable stall gave birth to a small grocery shop, there were less marketing efforts to employ, as many people were used to buying from her on a daily basis.

She continued to grow her business though at a very slow pace as she used to face acute working capital shortages from time to time. This pushed her to look for financial leverage and they came to Thrive. With this knowledge, Purity is realizing notable improvement in her restocking level and profits. This enabled her to buy some property for her kitchen and paying fees for her children. Purity got $500 to restock more groceries for her small shop.
name: White Horse Group
use: to restock more groceries for her small shop.

description.texts.en:
Beatrice is 62 years old, and is the married mother of six children who are still in school. She is a vegetable vendor; she plants and sells different vegetables, such as spinach, amaranth and cow peas. She has been running this business for 19 years, working every day from 6:30 a.m until 6:00 p.m. She earns profits from the business.

This will be Beatrice's second loan request from Tujijenge Tanzania. She used her previous loan to purchase seeds and fertilizer for planting vegetables to sell in the market. She earned profits that she used to support her family and reinvest in her business, and she managed to repay the loan on time.

She is applying for this loan to continue expanding her business by buying more vegetables seeds and fertilizers, as well as a big soaking tub to put her vegetables in for sale. Her dream is to become a large supplier of vegetables in the near future.

Beatrice will share a portion of this loan with her fellow member of Kimusi Grp Tarime-Unit Group. They promise to pay back the loan.
name: Kimusi Grp Tarime-Unit Group
use: to continue expanding her business by buying more vegetables seeds and fertilizers, as well as a big soaking tub to put her vegetables in for sale.
