description.texts.en:
Farai is a Shona name which means be happy. This name belongs to one ever-smiling woman who resides in the high density township of Dzivarasekwa Extension in Harare. Farai is a committed hard working woman involved in the cross border business. Farai travels to countries like Zambia and Mozambique supplying items like sheets, sofa covers and curtains. She outsources manufacturing of these items to local tailors in Zimbabwe.

Farai is a married mother of 5 children, and she is currently sending 4 of them to school. Her husband works as a driver for a transport company.

Farai and Sthembile are members of the Kresina group. They came to Thrive in August 2017 and received their first loan. They repaid their first loan very well and they testify that their businesses are growing. They hope that they continue growing their businesses. As a result they have approached Thrive Microfinance once again this year for an additional loan of $850 so as to improve their activities. Farai needs her portion of $500 so that she can buy more stock to sell in Mozambique.
name: Kresina Group
use: to buy more sheets, sofa covers and curtains to sell in Mozambique.

description.texts.en:
Sale is from a small community in Kaduna state where he grows maize to support his family. Sale has been a Babban Gona member for two seasons and as a result, he has been able to send two children to a better school with the profits from his farm.

Sale’s goal for this farming season is to double last year's yield. With this loan, he will gain access to improved seeds, fertilizers, herbicides and other inputs which are critical to increasing his yield to up to 4.2 metric tonnes per hectare, which is more than double the national average in Nigeria. This will enable him to generate earnings of up to four times the average Nigerian farmer’s annual income

Sale recalls sending his children to school as his happiest memory as a Babban Gona member. Sale looks forward to a brighter future with Babban Gona and to making many more great memories with his family.
name: Sale
use: to buy fertilizers and seeds in order to get a good harvest and earn more money.

description.texts.en:
Amosi is 22 years old and he is still single. He is a retailer and he owns a retail shop. He has been in this business for two years and normally works from 5:00 a.m. until 8:00 p.m. He earns good profit.

This will be Amosi's first loan request from Tujijenge Tanzania. He is applying for this loan to buy more stock of food items, soft drinks, detergents, kerosene, petroleum jelly, boxes of biscuits, and bites. His dream is to own a big fruit farm in the near future.

Amosi will be responsible for paying back the loan.
name: Amosi
use: to buy more stock of food items, soft drinks, detergents, kerosene, petroleum jelly, boxes of biscuits, and bites.

description.texts.en:
Education has become increasingly important in Zimbabwe. This needs to be taken into account especially by responsible mothers like Georgina. Given this, she decided to start a small business which helps her to generate income so that she can support her children financially.

Georgina is a member of a group called Blazio which she formed with her neighbor Violet. She farms poultry. She stays with her family in the suburb of Nkwisi Gardens in Harare, Zimbabwe. Her husband works at a local insurance company as a general hand. They have four children and all of them are going to school.

She has been in this business for six years. She got a loan from Thrive six months ago which she invested in her business. She has realized a significant rise in profits over the years. She restocks her broiler chickens from a local poultry company. She supplies chicken to canteens in her suburb as well as to those in neighboring suburbs.

Her fowl run has a capacity of 400 birds which allows her room to expand her business. Georgina wants her portion of the loan to buy more chickens.
name: Blazio Group
use: to buy more chickens.

description.texts.en:
Caroline is a 52-year-old woman who stays in Chegutu, Zimbabwe. She is a hard-working woman raising egg-laying chickens. She has a big fowl run in her backyard.

Currently, she has more than 50 chickens in her fowl run. She has been in this business for more than ten years. She has customers, mainly from tuck-shop operators in the local community.

Caroline's husband has retired and is now on a pension. So, her business income is an important source of the family’s income. They have three children, one of whom is still going to school.

Caroline and two other women (Lucia and Tambudzai) are members of the Mufaro Chegutu Group ('mufaro' is Shona for happiness). They came to Thrive Microfinance and went through financial training.

They have applied for a combined loan of USD 950. Caroline needs her portion of USD 350, so that she can buy chicken feed. She also plans to buy additional chickens, so as to grow her business.
name: Mufaro Chegutu Group
use: buy chicken feed for her chickens and additional chicks.

description.texts.en:
Ashura is 34 years old, single and is blessed with two school-going children. She is a green grocer, selling different cooking ingredients such as tomatoes, onions, coconuts, green vegetables and fruits. She has been in this business for four years, opening her grocery every day from 8 in the morning and closing at 6 in the evening. She earns a profit.

This will be Ashura's first loan request from Tujijenge Tanzania. She is applying for this loan to add more stock of coconuts, tomatoes, onions, peppers, green vegetables and fruits. Her dream is to own a retail shop in the near future. Ashura will share this loan with her loan group member of "Apple Segerea."
name: Apple Segerea Group
use: to add more stock of coconuts, tomatoes, onions, peppers, green vegetables and fruits.

description.texts.en:
Shaharu is from a small community in Kaduna state where he grows maize to support his family. Shaharu has been a Babban Gona member for one season, and as a result, he has been able to send two children to school with the profits from his farm.

His goal for this farming season is to be the best-performing farmer in his community. With this loan, he will get access to improved seed, fertilizer, herbicide and other inputs which are critical to increasing his yield to up to 4.2 metric tonnes per hectare, which is more than double the national average in Nigeria. This will enable him generate earnings of up to four times the average Nigerian farmer’s annual income.

Shaharu recalls opening an agro-dealer shop as his happiest memory as a Babban Gona member. He looks forward to a brighter future with Babban Gona and to making many more great memories with his family.
name: Shaharu
use: to buy fertilizer and seed to get a good yield and earn more money.

description.texts.en:
Katija is 30 years old and is a single mother of two school-going children. She is a very hardworking tailor. She has been in this business for a good five years. She usually works from 9:00 a.m. until 6:00 p.m. Her business is profitable.

This will be Katija's first loan request from Tujijenge Tanzania. She is applying for this loan to buy sewing tools and materials, such as scissors, measuring tapes, needles and threads. Her dream is to become the best designer in the near future.

Katija will be responsible for paying back the loan.
name: Katija
use: to buy sewing tools and materials, such as scissors, measuring tapes, needles and threads.

description.texts.en:
Starting off in bales business was not an easy game for Constance, but she managed to resist the competition by restocking her bales according to seasonal demand. The competition strengthened Constance’s resolve and she gained experience and exposure in business working hard at making her name well-known.

Constance is a thirty-nine-year-old mother of two who are both school-going. She is married and her husband is a soldier. Constance is using her portion of the loan to restock winter wear since seasonal selling has proven to work well. Since Constance restocks most of her products cheaply across the border, she plans to restock more winter wear to meet current demand. She also has the advantage of selling on credit and collecting her sales every weekend. She wastes no time resting but is always working.
name: Vimen Group
use: is to restock winter wear ahead of the cold season.

description.texts.en:
Shehu is from a small community in Kaduna state, where he grows maize to support his family. Shehu has been a Babban Gona member for two seasons and, as a result, he has been able to send one child to a better school with the profits from his farm.

Shehu’s goal for this farming season is to double last year's yield. With this loan, he will get access to improved seeds, fertilizers, herbicides, and other inputs that are critical to increasing his yield by up to 4.2 metric tons per hectare, which is more than double the national average in Nigeria. This will enable him to generate earnings of up to four times the average Nigerian farmer’s annual income.

Shehu recalls buying more farmland as his happiest memory as a Babban Gona member. Shehu looks forward to a brighter future with Babban Gona and to making many more great memories with his family.
name: Shehu
use: to purchase improved inputs to get a good harvest and earn more money.

description.texts.en:
Janeth is a hard-working mom of lovely children. To help her family, Janeth ventured into farming five years ago. Currently, she keeps cows and poultry on her farm for milk, meat, and eggs. She also makes extra money arranging the logistics of getting cereal produce from local farmers to their buyers.

She understands that for this business to be successful, she needs to rely on two things: relationships and capital. She has been able to build strong relationships in the nine years she has been farming, but what she seems to be lacking is capital to secure more cereal.

Janeth is seeking a loan of 30,000 Kenya shillings (KES) to buy cereals. She plans to use the money to buy more produce from local farmers at fair prices and use her better understanding of the market conditions and prices to sell at a profit.

She wants to start the next quarter of 2018 on a high note, and through the loan, she will be able to achieve this. Be inspired, and lend to Janeth today!
name: Janeth
use: to buy different varieties of cereals (lentils, cow peas, and rice) to sell in the local market and improve her living condition.

description.texts.en: The Laban Group just finished paying back their last Kiva loan. The repayments have been made on time. Fatoumat, who is the representative member of the group, would like to thank all the Kiva staff and lenders for their support. With the loan, Fatoumat was able to buy sugar and ingredients to make juices and sell them. She made some profits which were used for her family's and her own fulfillment, including paying for her children's schooling and above all to expand her business. Fatoumat still needs loans in order to keep her juice selling business running.
description.texts.fr: Laban vient de finir son prêt kiva. Les remboursements ont été fait normalement. Fatoumat, membre représentatif remercie tout le personnel et les prêteurs de kiva pour le soutien. Avec le prêt, Fatoumat a pu payer du sucre et les ingrédients pour ses jus et vendre. Elle a eu un bénéfice qui lui a permis de s'épanouir elle et toute sa famille, elle a pu payer la la scolarité de ses enfants et surtout d'augmenter son activité. Fatoumat a encore besoin de prêts pour continuer son activité de vente de jus.
name: Laban Group
use: to buy sugar and ingredients to make juice.

description.texts.en: Ouampousga is forty one years old, married and a mother. She sells cereals and she has been doing this business for ten years. She needs a loan to buy bags of corn, bags of millet, sorghum and peanuts to resell. Her selling counter at the market is well located, she is well-known given her experience, she is also respecteful and welcoming towards the customers, and moreover the products she sells are of good quality, all of this contributing to making her business a success. After selling these products, she will have some profits which will enable her to save up some money to take care of her family and also to keep her business running. This is currently her second loan contract wtih ACFIME and the repayments [from the previous loan] have been made on time.
description.texts.fr: Ouampousga est âgée de 41 ans, mariée et mère. Elle vend du céréale et cela fait 10 ans qu'elle exerce cette activité. Elle a besoin d'un prêt pour acheter des sacs de maïs, du petit mil, du sorgho et de l'arachide  pour vendre. Son emplacement du lieu de vente au marché est bien situé, elle est connue vu son expérience, elle est aussi respectueuse, accueillante envers ses clients en plus de cela tout ce qu'elle propose à ses clients est de qualité c'est tout cela qui fait bien marcher son activité. Après ses ventes elle aura un bénéfice qui lui permettra de faire des épargnes de s'occuper de sa famille et aussi de continuer ses activités. Elle est à son 2ème  contrat de prêt ACFIME et les remboursements se sont fait normalement.
name: Watitoumi Group
use: to buy bags of corn, bags of millet, sorghum and peanuts to resell.

description.texts.en:
Alfiado is 31 years old and lives with his partner. He is a retailer and the father of three children, of whom two are school-aged and in primary school and the other is still too young for school. He lives in a house he owns.
With the amount of the loan he intends to buy products: chairs, bundles of clothing, buckets, basins, brooms, mops, cups, and thermoses to re-sell.
He is a repeat client, and with the previous loans he invested in the same business.
He dreams of acquiring a space to develop his business.
description.texts.pt:
O senhor Alfiado têm  31 anos de idade, vive maritalmente, comerciante, pai de 3 filhos dos quais 2 em idade escolar frequentando o ensino primário e o outro sem idade escolar, vive na casa própria.
Com o valor do empréstimo pretende comprar produtos: cadeiras, sextos de roupa, baldinho, bacias, vassouras, mope, chávenas, copos, termos para posterior venda.
É cliente subsequente e com emprestimos anteriores investiu no mesmo negócio.
Sonha em adquirir um espaço para desenvolver o seo negócio
name: Alfiado
use: Alfiado to buy a variety of items to re-sell.

description.texts.en:
Olímpio is 45 years old and lives with his partner in a house they own. He is the father of nine children, of whom two are adults and the others are not. He is a retailer; he makes a living by buying and selling construction and plumbing material.
This is his second loan with HLUVUKU; he intends to use it to buy a variety of construction and plumbing material to re-sell. With the first loan, he bought merchandise for his store. After he finishes repaying this loan, he intends to ask for another to buy more furniture for his house.
He dreams of seeing his business more developed.
description.texts.pt:
O senhor Olímpio tem 45 anos de idade, vive maritalmente na casa própria. É pai 9 filhos, dos quais 2 são maiores e os outros são menores, é comerciante, dedica-se a compra e venda de material de construção e de canalização.
 Este é o segundo crédito junto a HLUVUKU pelo qual pretende comprar diverso material de canalização e construção para revenda, com o primeiro comprou mercadorias para a sua mercearia. Findo repagamento deste crédito pretende contraír outro para comprar mobilias para a sua casa.
Ele sonha em ver o seu negócio mais desenvolvido.
name: Olimpio
use: Olímpio to buy construction material to re-sell.

Shafi'u is from a small community in Kaduna state, Nigeria, where he grows maize to support his family. He has been a Babban Gona member for one season and as a result, he has been able to send two children to a better school with the profits from his farm.

Shafiu’s goal for this farming season is to double last year's yield. With this loan, he will gain access to improved seed, fertilizers, herbicides and other inputs, which are critical to increasing his yield to up to 4.2 metric tonnes per hectare. This is more than double the national average in Nigeria and will enable him to generate earnings of up to four times the average Nigerian farmer’s annual income.

Shafi'u recalls sending his children to school as his happiest memory as a Babban Gona member. He looks forward to a brighter future with Babban Gona and to making many more great memories with his family.
name: Shafi'u
use: to buy fertilizers and seed in order to have a good harvest and earn more money.

description.texts.en:
Suleiman is from a small community in Kaduna state where he grows maize to support his family. Suleiman has been a Babban Gona member for two seasons and as a result, he has been able to send three children to a better school with the profits from his farm.

Suleiman’s goal for this farming season is to double last year's yield. With this loan, he will get access to improved seed, fertilizers, herbicides and other inputs which are critical to increasing his yield to up to 4.2 metric tonnes per hectare, which is more than double the national average in Nigeria. This will enable him generate earnings of up to four times the average Nigerian farmer’s annual income

Suleiman recalls buying more farmland as his happiest memory as a Babban Gona member. Suleiman looks forward to a brighter future with Babban Gona and to making many more great memories with his family.

description.texts.en:
Memory is a 36 year old woman who buys and sells clothes. She travels to neighboring countries like South Africa and Zambia once or twice every month to buy trending clothes. For five years now she has been in this business and over time her business has recorded significant growth and she managed to open a small flea market in Harare’s Central business District. She is managing her business very well and has been casually employing someone to assist her when she is out of the country.

Memory is married and her husband is self-employed. She is staying in the suburb of Kuwadzana Harare. They have 2 children, both going to school. She depends upon income from her business and assistance from her husband in taking care of their children. Memory is a hardworking woman and is driven by the passion to take good care of her children.

Memory came to Thrive Microfinance in March this year and is applying for an individual loan of $800. She needs this loan so that she can boost up stocks for her flea market. She has plans to open another flea market soon. She plans to purchase winter stocks in bulk. She also runs a phone accessories which she wants to boost by increasing the size of her orders.
name: Memory
use: boost stocks for her clothing sales business.

description.texts.en:
Living is a repeat client of UGAFODE Microfinance Ltd (MDI). He has been a good client who has always paid his installments on time. He is 38 years old, married with six children who attend school.

Living's main source of income is agriculture, majoring in pineapple and banana growing done on a large scale. His main clients are the food markets in Ishaka and Mbarara. With the money he gets from this business, he educates his children and also supports some dependants.

Living is challenged with the transportation of his farm produce to the market. It is costly and most of the time it is unreliable. He has applied for a loan of 3,500,000 UGX from UGAFODE to buy a motorcycle, which he will use to transport his produce to the food markets. Living is hopeful that this will reduce his operational costs, thus increasing his profits. It will also enable him to make timely deliveries to his clients.

Living sends his gratitude to the funders for the financial empowerment. Living and his wife appear in the photograph in their plantation.
name: Living
use: to buy a motorcycle that will transport his produce to the market.

description.texts.en:
Rehema is a 34-year-old divorced mother of 4 school-going children. She is a hair dressing salon owner, and has been into this business for 3 years. She opens her salon at 8 a.m. and closes at 9 p.m. She earns profit.

This will be Rehema's first loan request from Tujijenge Tanzania. She is applying for this loan to buy a set of combs, hand dryer, hair steamer, shampoo bowl, and furniture.

Rehema's dream is to become a best make up artist. She will share this loan with her loan group members of Lisbon 2 Group.
name: Lisbon 2 Group
use: to buy a set of combs, hand dryer, hair steamer, shampoo bowl, and furniture.

Suleiman is from a small community in Kaduna state where he grows maize to support his family. Suleiman has been a Babban Gona member for two seasons and as a result, he has been able to send one child to a better school with the profits from his farm.

description.texts.en:
Esther is 18 years old and lives in the town of Namutumba in the Iganga region of Uganda. For the past 2 years, Esther has been working hard to manage her fish business, which sells smoked, dried and fried fish.

To help expand her business, Esther has requested a loan of 600,000 Ugandan Shillings from BRAC Uganda. The loan will be used to stock more fish for the business, and will help Esther to generate greater profits. From the higher profits, Esther will also provide basic needs like food at home, cater for her siblings, contribute to the respective school dues and thereby having better standards of living. Esther hopes that in the future she will be able to establish a retail business to increase on her revenue.

Esther is a member of BRAC's Empowerment and Livelihood for Adolescents (ELA) program. In addition to microfinance loans, the program provides both a safe place for young Ugandan women to take part in group activities, and a forum for life-skills training.
name: Esther
use: to stock more fish for her business.

description.texts.en:
Hadijja is 20 years old and lives in the town of Kaliro in the Iganga region of Uganda. For the past three years, Hadijja has been working hard to manage her restaurant where she sells cooked rice, beans, maize flour and green bananas.

To help expand her business, Hadijja has requested a loan of 900,000 Ugandan Shillings from BRAC Uganda. The loan will be used to buy bigger sauce pans, more rice, beans and maize flour, and will help Hadijja to generate greater profits. The business will expand and hence more profits. Hadijja will afford more basic needs and clothing and support her siblings, thereby improving her standard of living.

Hadijja hopes that in the future she will be able to expand the restaurant to a hotel.

Hadijja is a member of BRAC's Empowerment and Livelihood for Adolescents (ELA) program. In addition to microfinance loans, the program provides both a safe place for young Ugandan women to take part in group activities, and a forum for life-skills training.
name: Hadijja
use: to buy bigger sauce pans, more rice, beans and maize flour.

description.texts.en: John is happily married and, together with his wife, has been blessed with a child. He runs a grocery business in which he enjoys serving his clients. He intends to add more stock to meet growing demand. This is his second loan, which he will be able to pay back from the profits generated. He dreams of becoming a more successful business man in future.
name: John Kimiti
use: to add stock of fruits and vegetables.

description.texts.en:
Prossy is 22 years old and lives in the town of Kaliro, in the Iganga region of Uganda. For the past 2 years, Prossy has been working hard to manage her vegetables business, which sells tomatoes, eggplants, onions, and cabbages.

To help expand her business, Prossy has requested a loan of 200,000 Ugandan Shillings from BRAC Uganda. The loan will be used to buy a bicycle to ease the transportation of vegetables and purchase more vegetables, which will help Prossy to generate greater profits. Then Prossy will be in a position to afford more basic needs and also improve on her standards of living, contribute to the respective bills for medication and also cater for her siblings and contribute to their respective school dues. Prossy hopes that in the future she will be able to buy a plot of land and build a bricked house.

Prossy is a member of BRAC's Empowerment and Livelihood for Adolescents (ELA) program. In addition to microfinance loans, the program provides both a safe place for young Ugandan women to take part in group activities, and a forum for life-skills training.
name: Prossy
use: to purchase more vegetables and a bicycle for transportation.

description.texts.en:
Juliana is 23 years old and lives in the town of Iganga in the Iganga region of Uganda. She is married and has 2 children who are all currently in school. For the past 3 years, Juliana has been working hard to manage her business that sells charcoal.

To help expand her business, Juliana has requested a loan of 800,000 Ugandan Shillings from BRAC Uganda. The loan will be used to stock more charcoal for resale.

This will help Juliana to generate greater profits and he higher profits from expanded business will enable Juliana afford basic needs of life, improve her standards of living and cater for her children as well, in the same line pay the respective school dues.

Juliana hopes that in the future she will be able to buy a plot of land and build a brick house.

Juliana is a member of BRAC's Empowerment and Livelihood for Adolescents (ELA) program. In addition to microfinance loans, the program provides both a safe place for young Ugandan women to take part in group activities, and a forum for life-skills training.
name: Juliana
use: to stock more charcoal for resale.

description.texts.en:
Claire is 21 years old and lives in the town of Iganga in the Iganga region of Uganda. For the past three years, Claire has been working hard to manage her food stall where she sells green bananas, potatoes and cassava.

To help expand her business, Claire has requested a loan of 500,000 Ugandan Shillings from BRAC Uganda. The loan will be used to stock more green bananas and potatoes, and will help Claire to generate greater profits. From the higher profits, Claire will afford basic needs at home, cater for her siblings and contribute to the respective school dues, thereby improving her standard of living. Claire hopes that in the future, she will be able to build rental houses for more revenue.

Claire is a member of BRAC's Empowerment and Livelihood for Adolescents (ELA) program. In addition to microfinance loans, the program provides both a safe place for young Ugandan women to take part in group activities, and a forum for life-skills training.
name: Claire
use: to stock more green bananas and potatoes.

description.texts.en:
Amos is a male Ugandan aged 30 years and a resident of Omungyenyi, Rubaare Ntungamo where he has been operating his boutique business for 2 years after shifting it from Kitwe, a rural area.

Amos is a hardworking and honest person who believes in building a good customer background He takes this as his sole and main business where he works for at least 10 hours par day. He also saves some time to supervise and work in his banana plantation that he has generated out of his business.

Additionally, he is also taking care of his two children who are attending school and need him to sustain the business.

His business is strategic given the monopoly position he stands in the area and being on a high way to Kabale. He has been able to grow his business from hawking up to the one-stop center with out any external financial support.

Given the increasing demand for new fashions, he considers that additional capital from loan will help him to keep the leading position in the area while increasing on his returns.

He considers this financing a boost in his business as this will help him stock new and highly demanded items.
name: Amos
use: to buy more stock, especially shoes and new fashions.

description.texts.en:
Hello, Kiva community! Meet Abigael, a hardworking, determined woman, and a great achiever. She is a rural smallholder farmer from the Kapcherop area of Kenya. Her family's main revenue source is milk from their dairy farm. However, she also participates in some side businesses to complement her meager income.

The biggest problem that farmers from her village face is the huge discrepancy in their access to agricultural inputs, resulting in the fact that farmers' output and earnings are below what they could be. Juhudi Kilimo has partnered with Kiva to provide financial services to smallholders around Kenya. Through these financial services, farmers like Abigael can take out loans and purchase farm inputs.

Abigael is humbly seeking a loan to buy farm inputs such as fertilizer and high-quality seed. Your loan will enable her to improve her production, through the use of quality farm inputs. Abigael’s competitive advantage in the market will be evident after she receives this loan.

Through this intervention, she will be able to afford food for her loving family. She thanks Kiva lenders for their kindness.
name: Abigael
use: to buy farm inputs, such as certified quality seed and fertilizer, to improve her crop farming and eventually, through increased profits, improve her standard of living.

description.texts.en:
Khadija is 43 years old, married and blessed with 4 children, 2 boys and 2 girls, all of whom are students.

She sells beverages such as soda and mineral water. She has been into this business for over 10 years and works daily from 7 in the morning until 6 in the evening. Her business is doing good and she earns a profit.

This will be Khadija's 4th loan request from Tujijenge Tanzania. She purchased more stock of soda and water in her previous loans and earned a profit that she used to support her family needs. She also managed to pay back the loan successfully.

She is applying for this loan to buy more crates of soda, mineral water and to purchase a refrigerator.

Her dreams is to own a wholesale shop in the near future.

Khadija will share a portion of this loan with her loan group members of "Mafuriko".
name: Mafuriko Group
use: to buy more crates of soda, mineral water and purchase a refrigerator.

description.texts.en:
Jane is 17 years old and lives in the town of Kaliro in the Iganga region of Uganda. For the past year, Jane has been working hard to manage her produce business, which sells maize and cassava.

To help expand her business, Jane has requested a loan of 500,000 Ugandan Shillings from BRAC Uganda. The loan will be used to stock more beans and maize, and will help Jane to generate greater profits.

When Jane realizes more profits from the expanded business, she will be in position to improve on her standards of living and also cater for her siblings and contribute to the respective school dues.

Jane hopes that in the future she will be able to buy a plot of land and build a brick house.

Jane is a member of BRAC's Empowerment and Livelihood for Adolescents (ELA) program. In addition to microfinance loans, the program provides both a safe place for young Ugandan women to take part in group activities, and a forum for life-skills training.
name: Jane
use: to stock more beans and maize.

description.texts.en:
Jennipher's group is comprised of 2 hard working women. Jennipher is 17 years old and lives in the town of Kaliro in the Iganga region of Uganda. For the past 2 years, Jennipher has been working hard to manage her snack business, which sells chapati.

To help expand her business, Jennipher has requested a share of 1,100,000 Ugandan Shillings from BRAC Uganda. The loan will be used to stock more wheat, cooking oil and charcoa.

This will help Jennipher to generate greater profits and with higher profits from expanded business, Jennipher will support her siblings financially and hence improve on the standards of living at home and contribute to the respective school dues.

Jennipher hopes that in the future she will be able to venture into restaurant business and increase on her revenue.

Jennipher is a member of BRAC's Empowerment and Livelihood for Adolescents (ELA) program. In addition to microfinance loans, the program provides both a safe place for young Ugandan women to take part in group activities, and a forum for life-skills training.
name: Jennipher's Group
use: to stock more wheat, cooking oil and charcoal.

description.texts.en: Joseph is 28 years old and is happily married. He runs a motorcycle spare parts shop which caters to all his needs. He intends to use the loan to add stock to the business to meet demand. His main challenge has been not having a variety of product choices that customers can choose from. Assisting him with this loan will help him stock his shop well to enable him meet demand. He has serviced other loans with us before and he believes he will able to service this loan as well with his business profits. He dreams of giving his children a good education.
name: Joseph Wachira
use: to add stock of motorcycle spare parts.

description.texts.en:
Anna is happily married and through her occupation as a farmer she is able to support her family.

Her main challenge is lack of enough capital to boost her growing business. Through her business, she has managed to employ others who assist her in running her business.

Anna intends to use the loan to add stock of her farm inputs.

She aspires to one day own rental houses for added financial security.
name: Anna Wanjiru
use: to buy farm inputs.

description.texts.en:
Daniel is a 48-year-old married man. He lives with his wife and their three children in Koforidua, the Eastern Regional capital of Ghana. All of the three children are in school.

Daniel earns a living from the operation of a cold store, where he sells various kinds of meat – chicken, chevon, mutton, beef and fish. His main customers are restaurant operators in his community.

The growing population in his community is creating an increase in the demand for meat from his shop. He thus need financial assistance to be able to buy more meat products. It is in this light that he approached Advans Ghana for financial support to able to keep his customer by meeting their demands.

Daniel will appreciate the support from Kiva lenders to help him raise the money to stock his shop with meat. He looks forwards to save enough and open another point of sale in the community.
name: Daniel
use: to buy stocks of meat -- chevon, chicken, beef, fish -- for sale for increased revenue.

description.texts.en:
Joseph is a happily married man and through his occupation as a farmer he is able to support his family. Joseph's business has even managed to employ others to help him run his business.

His main challenge is lack of enough capital to boost his growing business to enable him sell more farm produce. He intends to use the loan to boost his business buy adding stock of more farm inputs.

He dreams of owning his own rental houses in future.
name: Joseph Muriithi
use: to buy farm inputs such as fertilizers.

description.texts.en:
Uwais is from a small community in Kaduna state where he grows maize to support his family. Uwais has been a Babban Gona member for one season and as a result, he has been able to send two children to a better school with the profits from his farm.

Uwais’s goal for this farming season is to learn new agronomic practices. With this loan, he will get access to improved seed, fertilizers, herbicides and other inputs which are critical to increasing his yield to up to 4.2 metric tonnes per hectare, which is more than double the national average in Nigeria. This will enable him generate earnings of up to four times the average Nigerian farmer’s annual income

Uwais recalls buying more farmland as his happiest memory as a Babban Gona member. Uwais looks forward to a brighter future with Babban Gona and to making many more great memories with his family.
name: Uwaisu
use: to purchase improved inputs in order to get a good harvest and enhance living standards.

description.texts.en:
Surajo is from a small community in Kaduna state where he grows maize to support his family. Surajo has been a Babban Gona member for one season and as a result, he has been able to send two children to a better school with the profits from his farm.

Surajo’s goal for this farming season is to double last year's yield. With this loan, he will get access to improved seeds, fertilizers, herbicides and other inputs which are critical to increasing his yield to up to 4.2 metric tonnes per hectare, which is more than double the national average in Nigeria. This will enable him generate earnings of up to four times the average Nigerian farmer’s annual income

Surajo recalls buying more farmland as his happiest memory as a Babban Gona member. Surajo looks forward to a brighter future with Babban Gona and to making many more great memories with his family.
name: Surajo
use: to purchase improved inputs in order to get a good harvest and earn more money.

description.texts.en:
Rehema is a 28-year-old divorced mother of four school-going children. She owns a pub that sells alcohol and soft drinks. She has been selling drinks for four years. She usually works from 5 in the evening to midnight, and she earns a profit.

This will be Rehema's third loan request from Tujijenge Tanzania. She used her previous loan to add more drinks in her pub. She earned a profit that she used to decorate her pub and pay school fees for her children. She managed to pay back the loan successfully.

She is applying for this loan to buy more stock of drinks such as alcohol and a crate of soda and add seats for her business to grow. Her dream is to invest in a big business.

Rehema promises to pay back the loan successfully.
name: Rehema
use: to buy more stock of drinks such as alcohol and a crate of soda and add seats for her business to grow.

description.texts.en:
Michael is 53 years old and the widowed father of 4 children who are still in school.

He own a butcher shop which sells beef, chicken and goat meat. He has been into this business for 30 years. He opens his business at 7:00 a.m and closes at 12:00 p.m daily. He earns a profit.

This will be Michael's 2nd loan request from Tujijenge Tanzania. He used his previous loan to buy more meat to sell and axes.

He earned good profit that used to cover his family's needs, pay government tax and cover some household expenses.
He managed to pay back the loan on time, too.

He is applying for this loan to buy more stock of fresh meat to sell such as goat meat, beef and chicken.

Michael will be responsible for paying back the loan successfully.

His dream is to open branches in the near future.
name: Michael
use: to buy more stock of fresh meat to sell such as goat meat, beef and chicken.

description.texts.en:
Peter is a happily married man who is happy to be able to support his family. He is a farmer a job he loves as it enables him to meet his needs.

He intends to add stock of more farm inputs to enable him produce higher quality produce so as to attract a larger market.

He has serviced previous loans well. He looks forward to owning his own rental houses in future.
name: Peter Joram
use: to buy farm inputs.

description.texts.en:
Emily is 56 years old and lives with her husband in the Eldoret area of Kenya. She is blessed with lovely children who are her greatest motivators. She perseveres because she wants to provide a better future for them.

Emily was unable to study for a professional career because of the economic situation in her family. However, she never gave up and she has been practicing farming for the past 10 years.

Emily has always had a great liking for farming. She has even nicknamed one of her cows and is a very proud farmer, especially when she is milking her cows. Her cows produce between 10 and 15 liters a day, which helps her support her family. She also practices crop farming, but she has not been making good profits because of poor farming inputs.

That is why Emily is seeking a loan to buy farm inputs. Through this loan, she will be able to purchase high quality seeds, good fertilizer, and pesticides that she will use to greatly improve her crop production. Modern farming requires the use of modern techniques, and high quality seeds will assure her of a bumper harvest and increased profits.

Kindly and humbly lend to this hardworking mom!
name: Emily
use: to buy farm inputs such as certified, quality seeds and fertilizer, to improve her crop farming and eventually, through increased profits, improve her standard of living.

description.texts.en:
Salehe is 28 years old and a married father of two children who are still in school. He is a motorcycle driver. He transports people from one place to another through his motorcycle known as bodaboda. He has been running this business for four years. He normally starts work every day at 8:00 am and closes at 8:00 pm. He earns a profit.

This will be Salehe's first loan request from Tujijenge Tanzania. He is applying for this loan to purchase another motorcycle known as bodaboda for his business to grow. His dream is to open a motorcycle spare parts business in the near future.

Salehe will share a portion of this loan with his loan group member of Ujamaa "b" Grp Musoma and they promise to pay back the loan
name: Ujamaa "b" Grp Musoma Group
use: to purchase another motorcycle known as bodaboda for his business to grow.

description.texts.en:
Prisca is a female, aged 35 years, living in Shamva, Zimbabwe with her husband and two children who are both in primary school. She has been running her flea market for 10 years. She has requested a loan from Microhub to purchase additional stock of jeans, t-shirts, shirts and shoes.

This income will help her boost her business, pay for her children's school fees, cover her rentals and general family expenses. Since the husband has a lower paying job, they heavily depend on this business for survival.
name: Prisca
use: to purchase additional stock of jeans, t-shirts, shirts and shoes.

description.texts.en:
Yusifa is from a small community in Kaduna state where he grows maize to support his family. Yusifa has been a Babban Gona member for two seasons and as a result, he has been able to send two children to a better school with the profits from his farm.

Yusifa’s goal for this farming season is to double last year's yield. With this loan, he will get access to improved seed, fertilizers, herbicides and other inputs, which are critical to increasing his yield to up to 4.2 metric tonnes per hectare, which is more than double the national average in Nigeria. This will enable him to generate earnings of up to four times the average Nigerian farmer’s annual income.

Yusifa recalls sending his children to school as his happiest memory as a Babban Gona member. Yusifa looks forward to a brighter future with Babban Gona and to making many more great memories with his family.
name: Yusifa
use: to buy fertilizers and seeds in order to get a good harvest and enhance his living standards.

description.texts.en:
Milka is a single mother who is happy to support her two children through her salon business. Her profits enable her to meet her needs as well as her family’s.

She intends to use the loan to add stock of more beauty products to meet the demand. It is her first loan and she intends to pay it back using the profits from the business. She dreams of owning her own rental houses in the future.
name: Milka Nyambura
use: to add stock of beauty products such as weaves, etc.

description.texts.en:
Jamila is 41 years old, married and blessed with three school-going children. She is a general store owner who sells food items, soft drinks and other goods. She has been in this business for seven good years. She normally opens her shop at 6:30 am and closes at 10:00 pm. Her business is doing good and she earns a profit.

This will be Jamila's first loan request from Tujijenge Tanzania. She is applying for this loan to buy more stock of food items, soft drinks, kerosene, detergents, bites and other necessities. Her dream is to own a big business in the near future.

Jamila will share a portion of this loan with her loan group members of Tumaini Group Chanika.
name: Tumaini Group Chanika
use: to buy more stock of food items, soft drinks, kerosene, detergents, bites and other necessities.

description.texts.en:
Rosemary is 22 years old and lives in the town of Kyengera in the Kyengera region of Uganda. For the past three years, Rosemary has been working hard to manage her retail business where she sells soap, bread, sugar, rice, and beans.

To help expand her business, Rosemary has requested a loan of 1,100,000 UGX from BRAC Uganda. The loan will be used to buy more inventory of sugar, salt, rice, and beans. This will help Rosemary generate greater profits so that she can afford life's basic needs, improve her standard of living, and help her siblings with paying school fees. Rosemary hopes that in the future she will be able to expand her retail shop and turn it into a wholesale business.

Rosemary is a member of BRAC's Empowerment and Livelihood for Adolescents (ELA) program. In addition to microfinance loans, the program provides both a safe place for young Ugandan women to take part in group activities and a forum for life-skills training.
name: Rosemary
use: to buy more inventory of sugar, salt, rice, and beans.

description.texts.en: Grace is a single mother who supports her grandchildren. She sells her commodities at the market place and enjoys the profits it brings. She intends to add stock to boost her business to meet demand. It is her first loan and she intends to use the profits from the business to pay back her loan and take others as her business continues to grow. She dreams of owning her own rental houses in the future to enable her to be financially stable.
name: Grace Wamutira
use: to add stock of fruits and vegetables.

description.texts.en:
Zakariyya is from a small community in Kaduna state where he grows maize to support his family. Zakariyya has been a Babban Gona member for two seasons and as a result, he has been able to send one child to a better school with the profits from his farm.

Zakariyya’s goal for this farming season is to double last year's income. With this loan, he will get access to improved seeds, fertilizers, herbicides and other inputs which are critical to increasing his yield to up to 4.2 metric tonnes per hectare, which is more than double the national average in Nigeria. This will enable him to generate earnings of up to four times the average Nigerian farmer’s annual income.

Zakariyya recalls building a better house for his family as his happiest memory as a Babban Gona member. Zakariyya looks forward to a brighter future with Babban Gona and to making many more great memories with his family.
name: Zakariyya
use: to buy fertilizers and seeds in order to get a good harvest and earn more money.

description.texts.en:
Alice is a 48-year-old businesswoman. She is a widow with three children, all of whom are enrolled in school while living at home. Alice runs a business where she sells charcoal by the bag. She established this business 10 years ago and has had no problems. Alice completed school through the sixth grade. She describes herself as a hardworking woman who sells six day a week, from 7:00 A.M. to 6:00 P.M.

Alice received some capital from her late husband to start her business and learned the trade from her mother. Her business is her only source of income, so she applied for a loan from BRAC Liberia. They money will be used to buy more bags of charcoal to sell so that she can increase her volume, sales, and profits. She transports inventory to her business by car. Alice enjoys her business because sales are fast and it helps her to pay her children's school fees. In the future, she would like to build a house. Alice expresses her thanks for the support from the lenders.
name: Alice
use: to buy more bags of charcoal to sell.

description.texts.en:
Anna is a single mother and farmer from a remote village in Kakamega, Kenya. She has defied the common thinking among Kenyans that agriculture is for the older generation. Anna is blessed with lovely children. Her primary source of income is milk, and she also plants maize on the farm.

Although she earns handsome profits from farming, Anna faces one big challenge: the high prices of fertilizers, seedlings, and other farming inputs. This is a result of the monopoly that is enjoyed by the only agrovet shop in her area.

Anna is requesting a loan to start her own agrovet shop. Her remote area has only one agro dealer, who caters to many smallholder farmers who solely depend on him for agricultural inputs. The agro dealer has been making a big profit from farmers by charging them extra, since he enjoys a monopoly.

Anna wants to change this and seize the business opportunity. With your loan, she will start an agrovet shop, and tap into the potential agricultural market. Anna will also help the smallholder farmers in her area who have, for a long time, been having a serious problem accessing affordable farm inputs.

You can be part of this dream. Go for it; make a loan.
name: Anna
use: to start an agrovet business (a shop for farm inputs such as animal feed, drugs, and pesticides).

description.texts.en:
Mpelwa is 27 years old and is a single father to one child who is still in school. He is a motorcycle driver who transports people from one place to another via his motorcycle, which is famously known as "Bodaboda". He has been in this business for four years. He works every day from 6:00 a.m until 9:00 p.m. His business is profitable.

This will be Mpelwa's second loan request from Tujijenge Tanzania. He used his previous loan to to repair his motorcycle and buy some spare parts for his business. He earned a good profit that he used to cover his family's needs and reinvest in his business. He managed to pay back the loan on time. He is applying for this loan to continue to expand his business by purchasing new spare parts and a seat cover as well as decorate his motorcycle to attract customers. His dream is to open a retail shop some day.

Mpelwa will be responsible for paying back the loan.
name: Mpelwa
use: to continue to expand his business by purchasing new spare parts and a seat cover as well as decorate his motorcycle to attract customers.

description.texts.en:
Afua is mother of four, living with the family in Tinkong, a community in Koforidua, the Eastern Regional capital of Ghana.

Afua has been into the selling of plastic products for the past seven years, an activity which has been the main source of income for the family. Due to her hard work and willingness to see the family doing well, she has added the selling of clothes to the sale of plastics. This is to enable her earn more income to meet the family’s expenses, especially the education of her children.

She currently needs financial assistance to enable her to buy more stocks of the plastic products and the clothes.

She intends to open another point of sale in future from the savings made from her extra profits.
name: Afua
use: to buy stocks of plastic products and clothes to sell for increased revenue.

description.texts.en:
Nura is from a small community in Kaduna state where he grows maize to support his family. Nura has been a Babban Gona member for two seasons and as a result, he has been able to send two children to a better school with the profits from his farm.

Nura’s goal for this farming season is to increase last year's yield. With this loan, he will get access to improved seed, fertilizers, herbicides and other inputs which are critical to increasing his yield to up to 4.2 metric tonnes per hectare, more than double the national average in Nigeria. This will enable him to generate earnings of up to four times the average Nigerian farmer’s annual income

Nura recalls sending his children to school as his happiest memory as a Babban Gona member. Nura looks forward to a brighter future with Babban Gona and to making many more great memories with his family.
name: Nura
use: to buy fertilizers and seeds in order to get a good harvest and enhance his living standards.

description.texts.en:
Jane is 23 years old and lives in the town of Buwama in the Kyengera region of Uganda. She is single and has one child. For the past three years, Jane has been working hard to manage her farm where she sells sweet potatoes, cassava, and maize.

To help expand her business, Jane has requested a loan of 1,000,000 UGX from BRAC Uganda. The loan will be used to buy fertilizers and pesticides, as well as employ more laborers. This will help Jane generate greater profits and expand her business so that she can afford more basic needs, such as clothing. She will be able to support her child and improve her family's standard of living. Jane hopes that in the future she will be able to to establish a raw foods export company and generate more revenue.

She is a member of BRAC's Empowerment and Livelihood for Adolescents (ELA) program. In addition to microfinance loans, the program provides both a safe place for young Ugandan women to take part in group activities and a forum for life skills training.
name: Jane
use: to buy fertilizers and pesticides, as well as employ more laborers.

description.texts.en:
Joseph is a resident of Jinja. He is married with school-going children.

He sells timber in Jinja suburbs, a business which has been his main source of income for five years. His clients are mainly construction sites in Jinja. Joseph started this business with the little savings he had accumulated from his former casual jobs. He started small but through re-investing into the business, the business has grown with an increasing clientele.

Joseph has applied for a loan of 3,000,000 UGX from UGAFODE to stock more timber for sale. He is optimistic that with increased stock, his sales will increase, and so will his income. 

He sends his sincere gratitude to the funders for the financial support that will boost his business as well as transforming his family's standards of living.

His future plan is to open a hardware shop to increase his income.
name: Joseph
use: to buy more lumber for sale.

description.texts.en:
Nuhu is from a small community in Kaduna state where he grows maize to support his family. Nuhu has been a Babban Gona member for one season and as a result, he has been able to send two children to a better school with the profits from his farm.

Nuhu’s goal for this farming season is to be the best performing farmer in his community. With this loan, he will get access to improved seed, fertilizers, herbicides and other inputs which are critical to increasing his yield to up to 4.2 metric tonnes per hectare, which is more than double the national average in Nigeria. This will enable him generate earnings of up to four times the average Nigerian farmer’s annual income

Nuhu recalls buying more farmland as his happiest memory as a Babban Gona member. Nuhu looks forward to a brighter future with Babban Gona and to making many more great memories with his family.
name: Nuhu
use: to buy fertilizers and seed in order to get a good harvest and earn more money.

description.texts.en:
In search of a better future for her family, which consists of her husband and her children, Pauline started mixed farming 10 years ago. Pauline is married to a fellow farmer. Her family's main income source is milk from their dairy farm. However, they are involved in other agricultural activities such as growing bananas and other fruits, vegetables and grains.

The biggest problem that farmers from her village face is the huge deficit in access to agricultural inputs, meaning that farmer's yields and incomes are far below what they could be. Juhudi Kilimo partnered with Kiva to provide financial services to smallholders around Kenya. Through these financial services, farmers from her village like Pauline can now buy productive assets and important agricultural inputs for use on their farms.

Pauline is seeking a loan to buy farm inputs such as seeds, fertilizer, herbicides and pesticides. Your loan will enable her to improve her production through the use of quality farm inputs. This intervention will help her fill the increasing demand for food in the market and, in the process, generate more income to repay the loan debt and improve the quality of life for her family.

Pauline hopes to improve the conditions of her house. Help this mother to accomplish all her dreams with just a loan!
name: Pauline
use: to buy farm inputs such as certified, quality seeds and fertilizer, to improve her crop farming and eventually, through increased profits, improve her standard of living.

description.texts.en:
Harriet is 20 years old and lives in the town of Kayunga in the Njeru region of Uganda. She is married and has two children with one of them currently in school.

For the past three years, Harriet has been working hard to manage her fast food business where she sells chips, sausages, chicken and beef.

To help expand her business, Harriet has requested a loan of 600,000 Ugandan Shillings from BRAC Uganda. The loan will be used to stock more Irish potatoes, cooking oil and spices, and will help Harriet to generate greater profits. From the higher profits, Harriet will afford basic needs at home, cater for her children, and pay the respective school dues, thereby improving her standard of living.

Harriet hopes that in the near future she will be able to establish a restaurant.

Harriet is a member of BRAC's Empowerment and Livelihood for Adolescents (ELA) program. In addition to microfinance loans, the program provides both a safe place for young Ugandan women to take part in group activities, and a forum for life-skills training.
name: Harriet
use: to stock more Irish potatoes, cooking oil and spices.

description.texts.en:
Faith is a determined woman who has only one thought in her mind: to prosper. She is a farmer from the Machakos area, Kenya who has a great sense of fashion. She is responsible for all the operations on her farm, which she does perfectly. On her farm, she rears dairy cows and poultry, grows crops, and carries out daily household chores such as cooking, collecting water, and caring for children.

She has been doing agriculture for 12 years now. She makes money selling produce from her farm, including milk, eggs and crops. She enjoys plowing her farm and watering her plants. Crop diseases pose a big challenge for her as well as poor productivity.

Faith is seeking an emergency loan to buy good quality seeds and fertilizer, which will help increase soil fertility and productivity on her farm. Increased productivity will allow her to improve her quality of life and her living standards. Through training from Juhudi Kilimo, she has learned about the culture of saving, and she plans to use the increased income to improve her farming.

This loan will go a long way in changing the lives of Faith and her family members. Faith dreams of building a modern house where her family can have an amazing quality of life.

Kindly and humbly support this hardworking mom and loan now.
name: Faith
use: as an emergency loan to buy good quality seeds and fertilizer, which will help increase soil fertility and productivity on her farm.

description.texts.en:
Shadia is 16 years old and lives in the town of Kayunga in the Njeru region of Uganda. For the past 1 year, Shadia has been working hard to manage her Grocery business, which sell green bananas, sweet potatoes, Irish potatoes and tomatoes.

To help expand her business, Shadia has requested a loan of 300000 Ugandan Shillings from BRAC Uganda. The loan will be used to stock more green bananas, sweet potatoes, Irish potatoes and tomatoes.

This will help Shadia to generate greater profits. As the business will expand and earn more profits, Shadia will afford more basic needs and clothing and support her siblings thereby improving on the standards of living.

Shadia hopes that in the future she will be able to buy a plot of land and build a family house.

Shadia is a member of BRAC's Empowerment and Livelihood for Adolescents (ELA) program. In addition to microfinance loans, the program provides both a safe place for young Ugandan women to take part in group activities, and a forum for life-skills training.
name: Shadia
use: to stock more green bananas, sweet potatoes, Irish potatoes and tomatoes.

description.texts.en:
Brendah is 19 years old and lives in the town of Kayunga in the Njeru region of Uganda. For the past 1 year, Brendah has been working hard to manage her business, which sells bed sheets.

To help expand her business, Brendah has requested a loan of 900,000 Ugandan Shillings from BRAC Uganda. The loan will be used to stock more second-hand bed sheets.
Increasing the stock will make more revenue , and will help Brendah to generate greater profits.

As business expands and profits increase, Brenda will be in position to improve the standards of living, support her siblings and contribute to the respective school dues as well.

Brendah hopes that in the future she will be able to go back to school and finish her studies.

Brendah is a member of BRAC's Empowerment and Livelihood for Adolescents (ELA) program. In addition to microfinance loans, the program provides both a safe place for young Ugandan women to take part in group activities, and a forum for life-skills training.
name: Brendah
use: to stock more second-hand bed sheets to get more revenue.

description.texts.en:
Sylvia is 18 years old and lives in the town of Kayunga in the Njeru region of Uganda. For the past 3 years, Sylvia has been working hard to manage her grocery store, which sells dried fish, tomatoes, silver fish and eggplant.

To help expand her business, Sylvia has requested a loan of 1,000,000 Ugandan Shillings from BRAC Uganda. The loan will be used to stock more dried fish, tomatoes, silver fish and eggplants, and will help Sylvia to generate greater profits because business will expand, profits will increase.

Then Sylvia will be in position to improve the standards of living, support her siblings and contribute to their respective school dues as well.

Sylvia hopes that in the future she will be able to buy a plot of land and build a family house.

Sylvia is a member of BRAC's Empowerment and Livelihood for Adolescents (ELA) program. In addition to microfinance loans, the program provides both a safe place for young Ugandan women to take part in group activities, and a forum for life-skills training.
name: Sylvia
use: to stock more dried fish, tomatoes, silver fish and eggplant.

description.texts.en:
Siwajibu is 24 years old and is single. She is into arts where she use woods to make different crafts. She has been into this business for 6 years. She usually works from 10 in the morning and closes at 6 in the evening. She earns a profit.

This will be Siwajibu's 1st loan request from Tujijenge Tanzania. She is applying for this loan to buy more wood, colors, nails, hammer and screws. Her dreams is to own a big business in the near future.

Siwajibu will be responsible for paying back the loan.
name: Siwajibu
use: to buy more wood, colors, nails, hammer and screws.

description.texts.en:
Isaac is 27 years old and is not yet married. He runs a cereal and beverage shop which helps him meet his daily needs.

He intends to add stock to his retail shop to enable him meet his business needs.

He will pay back the loan from the profits he generates from the business. He has serviced previous loans well.

Isaac looks forward to having his own retail shop in future.
name: Isaac Ngari
use: to add a stock of cereals.

description.texts.en:
Moreen is 17 years old and lives in the town of Kayunga in the Njeru region of Uganda. For the past 2 years, Moreen has been working hard to manage her Beauty Salon where she plaits hair, sells weaves and braids.

To help expand her business, Moreen has requested a loan of 1,000,000 Ugandan Shillings from BRAC Uganda. The loan will be used to buy a new dryer, more braids and salon oils, and will help Moreen to generate greater profits.

Then Maureen will be in position to afford more basic needs and also improve on her standards of living, also to cater for her siblings by contributing to their respective bills for the medication and school dues.

Moreen hopes that in the future she will be able to buy a plot of land and build a family house.

Moreen is a member of BRAC's Empowerment and Livelihood for Adolescents (ELA) program. In addition to microfinance loans, the program provides both a safe place for young Ugandan women to take part in group activities, and a forum for life-skills training.
name: Moreen
use: to buy a new dryer, more braids and salon oils.

description.texts.en:
Mercy is a mom who is humble, kindhearted and enterprising. She lives together with her children, in a rural area in Eldoret, Kenya. Her children are showing much interest in farming and even accompany her to the farm. Her family’s main source of income is selling milk produced by their dairy animals.

Mercy also engages in other agricultural activities, all of which are aimed at improving her family's standards of living. As the cost of agricultural production in the Kenyan rural lands continues to skyrocket, acquiring land and inputs has become a difficulty for many farmers. 

Mercy is seeking a loan to buy farm inputs such as fertilizers and quality hybrid seeds. 

Your loan will enable her to improve her farm production. This intervention will help her fill the increasing demand for food in the market and, in the process, generate more income to repay the loan debt and improve the quality of life for her family. She hopes to improve the conditions of her house.

Help this mother to accomplish all her dreams with this loan.
name: Mercy
use: to buy farm inputs such as fertilizers and quality hybrid seeds which will generate more income to repay the loan debt and improve the quality of life for her family.

description.texts.en:
Tricia is 20 years old and lives in the town of Kangulumira in the Njeru region of Uganda. She is married and has one child who is currently in school. For the past 1 year, Tricia has been working hard to manage her Fish Selling business.

To help expand her business, Tricia has requested a loan of 400,000 Ugandan Shillings from BRAC Uganda. The loan will be used to stock more fresh fish and more wire mesh for the ones to be smoked, and will help Tricia to generate greater profits.

With higher profits from expanded business, Tricia will support her child financially, improve on the standards of living at home and contribute to the school dues. Tricia hopes that in the future she will be able to buy a plot of land and build a family house.

Tricia is a member of BRAC's Empowerment and Livelihood for Adolescents (ELA) program. In addition to microfinance loans, the program provides both a safe place for young Ugandan women to take part in group activities, and a forum for life-skills training.
name: Tricia
use: to stock more fresh fish and more wire mesh for the ones to be smoked.
